title: For Sale/Trade:  FN Mauser 98 action barreled to a custom barrel
postcontent: I have come into an FN Mauser 98 action that has been custom fitted to a .300 Winchester magnum Douglas barrel.  The whole thing has been fitted into a makeshift synthetic stock, presumably for testing purposes and I was told it shoots very well.  The original owner/maker is a local (still practicing) gunsmith who was going to turn this into a benchrest/long range rifle.  The Douglas barrel is long and heavy.  I have not measured it but I am thinking 26-28" long and as heavy as a bull barrel.  I was going to buy an aftermarket stock and new bottom metal for it (with no lock screw holes) and have lost interest in doing so. The current bottom metal is fine, it just has the lock screws that I do not care for.  It is in excellent shape, the barrel is brand new and the action has been drilled and tapped for scope mounts.  I will include the mounts that came with it.  It has also been fitted with an additional safety unit on the trigger assembly.  Open to trades and offers if you'd like a project.  The barrel alone is a nearly $400 unit, plus the action and proper fitting.  I would guesstimate it's value in the $600-800 range.  New stock and bottom metal can be procured through Brownells or Midway and you could spend anywhere from $150/both to $1,000/both depending on what you wanted to do.  Gun shoots fine in the synthetic stock it's in, it's just not pretty.

title: For Sale:  Small Pistol Primers CCI 500 lancelynch@gmail.com
location: Garner, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I was trying to sell primers, if someone needed them. The cheapest that I saw across the nation is $55....... up to $100 per thousand.
I refused to sell mine for less than $60 because a buyer would be buying them to resale instead of using them.
I was trying to help, but now, I'll just pull them from sale,
I have been accused of gouging.   "your type makes me sick"  "I hope you choke on your profit"
Well, first, in legal definition, price gouging is "rapid increase in price for necessary goods during a civil emergency".
Otherwise, in a free capitilistic economy, it's just windfall profits.
Is it price gouging if you invest $100 in stock market and, 12 months later, your investment is worth $600? No! You'll be bragging to relatives and friends about your great investment.
This is what we have today, a free market. Some, like me, have invested in weapons and ammo their whole life, while others bought video games, ski boats and other crap that today is not worth a dime. It was YOUR choice.
When an item is offered and it is too expensive for you, don't try to buy it. The market will regulate what an item is worth.
Check out .22 ammo. In the past 10 years, I have bought maybe 75,000 rounds for $16 - $18 per box. That's less than 3 cents per round. Today, You'll be lucky to find any for less than 15 cents per round. It doesn't matter to me. I already have all that I need.

Just a little economic lesson for the day for the finger pointers that speak with an uneducated voice........ or maybe, they really are that stupid.
I  am amazed at how many people publish this "price gouging" garbage.
